---
/**
 * Braird plain-language explainer (SUR-709). Google's OAuth branding review
 * bounced the app for not stating its purpose in plain words — the rest of the
 * front door is deliberately evocative ("Every note finds its kin"). This band
 * is the one factual section a reviewer can point to: what braird is, the three
 * things it does, and the single Google scope it uses.
 *
 * Kept quiet on purpose — UI font, no Lora — so it reads as fact, not lyric.
 * No visible heading by request; named for assistive tech via aria-label.
 */
---

<section class="bf-what bf-dots" aria-label="What braird is">
  <div class="bf-wrap">
    <div class="bf-what-body">
      <p class="bf-what-lead">
        <strong class="bf-what-name">braird</strong> is a private app for readers. It captures
        the highlights and notes you make — across books, articles, and podcasts — and turns
        them into one searchable archive that connects related ideas from everything you've read.
      </p>

      <ul class="bf-what-fns">
        <li>
          <span class="bf-what-fn">Capture</span>
          <span class="bf-what-fn-text">Save highlights and notes from books, articles, and podcasts.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="bf-what-fn">Organize</span>
          <span class="bf-what-fn-text">Everything becomes one connected, searchable archive.</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="bf-what-fn">Sync</span>
          <span class="bf-what-fn-text">Your notes are encrypted, kept in your account, and synced across your devices.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p class="bf-what-scope">
        braird uses your Google account only to sign you in — your name and email.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
